Description

A computer aided dispatch (CAD) assists an organization with sending mobile services where they are needed. In public safety, computer aided dispatch software assists 911 operators and first responders to record and organize current needs. It helps everyone in the organization understand both their individual mission and what everyone else within the agency is doing. An official description can be found in the Department of Homeland Security Tech Note flier (2011) which states:

“ Computer-aided dispatch (CAD) systems are utilized by dispatchers, call-takers, and 911 operators to prioritize and record incident calls, identify the status and location of responders in the field, and effectively dispatch responder personnel. “

While a CAD system can provide numerous features to an agency, its basic purpose is to keep an agency informed on both current incidents and the status of first responders in the field.

CAD systems are generally limited to desktop applications. This improves security relative to a web application, but also requires first responders have access to a computer to use it. Although CAD software is usually on a laptop in a vehicle, it is often not accessible when first responders are out of their vehicle, or if they are not using a laptop at all. One way to alleviate this issue is by using a cell phone application.

A Mobile Computer Aided Dispatch displays the same information as a desktop CAD system, but placed on a cell phone application. This allows first-responders, supervisors, and administrators to review what is happening so long as they have access to a working cell phone. There are additional benefits to mobile CAD as well. Since CAD systems increasingly adopt GPS tracking to keep track of staff locations, they provide an added safety benefit when a first responder becomes lost or stops responding on the radio. GPS tracking a first-responder’s cell phone is likely to show a more accurate location to send help to. This is more useful than tracking the GPS location of a laptop inside a patrol car (assuming the cell phone wasn’t left in the vehicle). With the benefits of a CAD system being placed on a cell phone safety and security should be strongly evaluated before a first responder accesses their cell phone in the field. This is a resource, but it is up to the individual and the agency itself to determine when it is a safe and appropriate resource to use.

I built a prototype mobile computer aided dispatch application intended for first responders. There are primarily two types of users of a CAD system: Dispatchers who both read and update the data, and first-responders who primarily read the data. My application is meant to keep first responders informed on current incidents and everyone’s status. It is not meant to be used to create and update data. My CAD application also does not implement any additional features that often come with a CAD system and will focus on the primary goals of a CAD system.

**CadDispatcherBotConsole (C# Console Application):**

A Cad project would not be very interesting or testable without some data to consume! Since a computer aided dispatch is intended to show real-time and continuously changing data, I decided to create a Console application that would automate the role of a dispatcher for testing my application. I built my console application in C# because it is what I was most familiar with. I attempted to limit the amount of multithreading this console application used because I planned to either run it simultaneously on the same computer that was running my cell phone emulator, or I would run this on a backup computer with limited processing power. The console application has a few key classes that I will briefly describe:

CallScript.cs:

- The CallScript class contains attributes that describe how a Call should progress in the application. The call script contains an information on how to create a new call for service, the number of units the call will require, and a list of call comments to add to the call.

RandomCallScriptGenerator.cs

- The RandomCallScriptGenerator class is a completely static class. It contains a list of approximately 25 hardcoded call scripts I created, and a static method to get one randomly selected call script from the list. It is used to randomly add a new call to be created.

CallScriptTracker.cs

- Each instance of CallScriptTracker keeps track of the progress of one CallScript. As the call progresses, the call script tracker has conditional attributes that indicate the progress of the call so far. The class also uses a semi-random timeout period that is used each time the call progresses. The timeout period ensures there is a more natural pause between call events from start to finish. Without this timeout period, the script would run in its entirety as fast as the computer could perform the operations. The life cycle of a call script is shown below. This sequence does not fully replicate the complexities of a real call for service, but it is enough to test the application.

Create the Call -> Assign units to the call ->

Show units en-route to the call -> Show the units on-scene ->

Add one call comment at a time -> close the call

CadSimulator.cs

- The CadSimulator class simulates the activity of a dispatcher and runs continuously in a loop for the duration of the program. The Cad Simulator contains a list of CallScriptTrackers representing the current active calls for the agency. The list is initially empty at the start of the program. The Cad Simulator iterates over the list and checks if each of the element’s timeout period is up. If the timeout period is up, it attempts to take the next action on the call, which involves sending updates to the database. If the database was updated successfully, it notifies the call script tracker to progress to the next stage. If am update is unsuccessful, the CallScriptTracker is not notified and remains in the same state as before to retry the action in the next iteration. After the Cad Simulator iterates over the full list, it removes any finished call script trackers from the list. It then has a chance to add a new call to the list using a semi-random algorithm. Here is the pseudocode showing what this class does:

While (true):

Foreach (callScriptTracker in trackerList):

If (this callScriptTracker’s timeout period is up):

Take the next action on this element.

If (action was successful):

Update this callScriptTracker

Wait for between 1 and 10 seconds. . .

Remove any CallScriptTrackers from the list that are finished.

Invoke method to decide whether to add a new item to the list or not.

Wait for 10 seconds. . .

Repeat...

**CadApi (ASP.NET web API):**

To communicate to my database, I built an ASP.NET Web API to handle data requests. I used ASP.NET with C# because I had been using ASP.NET and was most familiar with it. I initially built the API using Entity Framework Core and an in-memory relational database. My plan was originally to have my Flutter application consume this API before switching to Firebase. Once I decided to migrate to Cloud Firestore, my Flutter application no longer used this web API. Even though I removed some of the purpose of this API, I was able to save my console application from any significant changes because all the database migration changes from a relational database to Firebase were done within this API.

The Web API uses the Repository pattern with the following directories:

| Controllers | Listens for HTTP Requests on the given URL endpoints and communicates to the services to access data. Returns Http Responses back to the client/user. |
| --- | --- |
| Models | The class models and data transfer object models are used for data and API requests/responses and to transform to and from the JSON format. |
| Repositories | Directly access and update Cloud Firestore Collections and Sub-collections. The repositories do not have any of the “business logic” and only know how to manipulate data on command from services. |
| Services | Receive requests from the Controller to perform operations. The service maps JSON data into class models and gives commands to repositories. One service request could involve multiple repository operations. |

**Docker Compose:**

I placed the console application and Web API into Docker containers and use Docker Compose to start them. By using docker compose, my console application uses a container network to send request to the API. The container network’s URL path remains the same, ensuring that my console application has valid URL endpoints when attempting to send requests. Initially, using Docker Compose was also intended to help my Flutter application consume the API before migrating to Cloud Firestore.

**ComputerAidedDispatchDB (Cloud Firestore):**

I initially intended to use an in-memory relational database for my application. As I was learning about how to provide real-time data to my application, I found that Http requests were not an efficient way to provide real-time data. The best option was to use a web socket to maintain a constant server-client connection and receive updates as fast as the back end could notify the client. I spent some time how to implement my own web sockets. The implementation was feasible, but it was challenging and would have added significant complexity to my application.

Once we were introduced to Cloud Firestore, it was the obvious choice to use with my application. By using Cloud Firestore, all the functionality of web sockets was already included. Firebase and Flutter also work very well together, both because the client library is robust and because there is a lot of good documentation on how to implement Firebase with Flutter. This was my first time working with a non-relational / no-SQL database, so I was on a time crunch to migrate to Cloud Firestore to meet goals for this application. For this reason, I am using my database in test-mode without implementing the database rules.

An interesting challenge I faced was that I could create a lot of reads and writes simulating CAD activity in Cloud Firestore. I had to routinely watch my data usage. My data usage typically spiked on Sundays and Mondays when I had the most time to work on the project.

Database Collections:

- CallForService represents an event or incident that first responders go to.
- Unit represents an individual first responder.
- UnitSummary is a sub-collection of CallForService. It represents a Unit that is assigned to the given CallForService.
- CallComment is a sub-collection of CallForService. It represents new information that dispatch adds to the call after its creation.
- CallSummary is a sub-collection of Unit. It represents a call for service which a unit is assigned to.

While CallForService and Unit are both top level collections, they both use sub-collections that refer to one another. A CallForService has a sub-collection of UnitSummaries assigned to it, representing units that are assigned to a call. A Unit has a sub-collection of CallSummaries assigned to it, representing the Calls the unit is assigned to. Each document (entity) is identified via its Id. Adding sub-collections with the same data as top level collections added some complexity when writing to the database, but it also allows the client application to quickly obtain the data to display a screen in a single read without the need to navigate multiple tables such as in a relational database. One way I was able to greatly simplify the code was by using identical Id’s for CallForService documents and their equivalent CallSummary documents, as well as Unit documents and their equivalent UnitSummary documents. This way, If I only have a summary sub-collection document, but decide I need to access the full document from the top-level collection, I can simply use the exact same Id to get the full top-level document in a single read operation instead of running a more complex query.

I am also using Firebase’s Authentication to authenticate users. By authenticated users, I can provide information customized to the individual user, mainly in the form of a user dashboard on the home page.

Challenges Encountered

One challenge I had from experience, was to constantly feed updates to the Flutter application without hindering the user experience. In my own experience, other Cad systems would reset the screen position to the top of the screen every time the data updated, or the screen would dim and become disabled for a split second every time a small data change occurred. On a very busy call, this could be infuriating if I needed data near the bottom of a scrollable screen, only to have the screen repeatedly reset at the top. I wanted to prevent this in my application. The solution was to make my screens stateless widgets and to lower state down so that it had less of an impact on the UI. I placed stateful widgets that display data from the database as far down the widget tree as possible so that they only updated a small portion of the screen. I relied heavily on the Provider package to update individual stateful widgets nested within the screen.

The solution above worked for the most part, but I encountered a strange problem. My application worked fine when I scrolled down a screen, but the screen would jump while scrolling back up to the top. The problem was that my stateful widgets stopped automatically using state when they scrolled off the top of the screen as I was scrolling down. This caused my display to jump when I scrolled back up and those stopped stateful widgets came back to life. The solution was to use the AutomaticKeepAliveClientMixin. Using this mixin forced the child widgets to remain alive even when off screen, so the screen did not have to constantly stop and start widget state when scrolling up and down. The mixin only required one line of code to implement. I was concerned that this may keep the Widgets alive TOO long after I was done with a screen, and thus create a memory leak. I tested this and luckily, the widgets still closed correctly upon switching to a new screen.

Another challenge was how to display address information in a single row of a list tile. I initially used a trick we were shown on a class link on Containers. The trick was to wrap the text in a FittedBox in an Expanded widget. This adjusted the size of the text as needed. The problem was that, for really long or really short addresses, the text would either be unacceptably small, is comically big for the tile. The solution was to keep my font size constant, and to use an ellipsis in the Text widget’s overflow parameter. This caused the address to cut off at the end for long addresses, but kept this Text at an acceptable size. Within the call details screen, I wrapped the address to ensure the entire address was listed on the screen.

Using authentication allowed the application to provide a customized dashboard for the user, but a problem figuring out how to link the signed in user to the corresponding Unit document in the Unit collection. By using the same Id for the Unit as the corresponding User, I was able to efficiently connect a user with their Unit document.

My application contains several Listviews that contain a dynamic list of data (calls lists, call comment lists, unit lists, etc). I wanted to be able to scroll up and down a whole screen even with several Listviews and other widgets nested inside. Listviews nested inside of listviews also threw an exception when created. The solution was to pass two parameter values to all nested Listviews: Set shrinkWrap to true and set physics to ClampingScrollPhysics. These two parameters removed the scrolling functionality and left scrolling up to screen widget.

I built this application using a dark theme with slightly lighter surfaces used to represent elevation in the UI, such as user dashboards. I initially used opacity values to shade surfaces with a given percentage opacity value. This worked well most of the time, but made some screens appear bugged during sliding animations from one screen to another and made some widgets appear behind opaque backgrounds while scrolling when I really wanted them to be fully hidden. The solution was to convert the opaque color (RGB value with opacity) to its equivalent RGB value, so that each surface was a solid color. I used a simple formula to convert an opaque color to a solid color.

For each Red, Green and Blue value:

SolidColor = foregroundColor – opacity \* (foregroundColor – backgroundColor)

This formula did not produce the exact same color as the opaque version, but it was close enough to make it was worth using. I also had to round the resulting values to a whole number for the RGB values in Flutter.

The last problem I encountered was with the StreamProvider class. StreamProvider is instantiated with an object type to listen for, and a service that gives it a stream of updated data of that type. The StreamProvider also required me to pass it an object to initialize it with prior to receiving any data from the stream/database. Listening to a list with StreamProvider was easy, as I could initialize it with an empty list before getting my actual database list. I encountered issues when attempting to listen to a specific document. The issue was that I could not initialize StreamProvider with a null value, because null was not a valid type. For instance, if I was listening for changes to a Unit on the unit details screen, I could not initialize the StreamProvider with null because null is not the same as the Unit class.

I attempted to change my StreamProvider and my corresponding service to listen for a nullable object, however StreamProvider still was unhappy with initializing as null even if the type it was listening for was declared nullable. To work around this problem, I loosened up the model classes to allow nullable fields. The StreamProvider then was initialized with an object containing all null values before the stream updated it with a new object filled with the correct values. This should be avoided because I initialized an object in an invalid state.

New Skills Learned

This project was both challenging and fun. It challenged me to learn the new skillsets required to build my application, and was fun so I maintained motivation to learn the skills needed to build this project.

First off, building my Console application enhanced my knowledge of dependency injection and asynchronous coding. I had never implemented dependency injection into a console application before building this application.

In my Web API, I learned how to apply the repository pattern to NO-SQL databases. I quickly learned that a good program design goes a long way to simplify the code needed to perform database operations. The biggest challenge of all was figuring out how to perform a write operation that required updating multiple collections.

To ensure my Web API and my Console application functioned correctly, I used Docker and Docker Compose. While using Docker Compose, I learned how to create a network between containers, which ensured my console application would always be able to communicate to my API.

With using Cloud Firestore, I learned how NO-SQL databases work and their advantages in read operations as opposed to a relational database. I also learned how keys work in Firebase differently than a relational database, as well as the basics of Firebase Authentication. I also learned how to perform queries in Firestore, including Collection Group Queries across multiple sub collections.

While building my Flutter application, I had to review several subjects that were introduced this semester, including the provider package, route navigation, database access, and containers. I also learned new ways to connect to a database via StreamProvider and Service classes.

When working with my data models that represent data, I had to thoroughly review Dart data structures, in particular learning more about how to implement maps and iterables.

While I only scratched the service of Flutter animations, I learned about how to introduce sliding transitions when switching screens and about implementing a Tween.

I reviewed a lot of information on UI themes, including contrast standards for accessibility and generally accepted best practices. I am not certain that my UI meets accessibility requirements as is, however I am confident that I would only need to make minor modifications to do so.
